<h3>
Presentation 1: Expanding Sentience: Ethics of Care and Animal
Individuality
</h3>

<h3>
Author
</h3>
<p>
Nia Baker
</p>

<h4>Nia Baker (Swansea University)
</h4>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>Human-animal relations have evolved exponentially over time and shape
how we think about animals today. This has centred largely on the divide
between utilitarian grounds for animal welfare (Singer, 1975) and the rights-
based approach of animal rights (Regan, 1983). However, there is much
room to consider our emotional obligations to animals including the
contributions of care ethics, empathy and sensitive philosophy (Donovan,
1996; Midgley; 1983). This literature review incorporates ecofeminist
arguments with green critiques of sentience to highlight the role of
emotions and connectivity in recognising the ‘animal individual’. The study
evaluates how a caring ethical framework can challenge speciesism and
the anthropocentric roots underpinning the ‘property’ status of animals in
legislation. This is also linked to the dismissal of ‘the animal self’ within
institutionalised harms and abuse. Doing so holds important implications for
a green criminology that promotes species justice and calls for ecocentric
discussion in mainstream criminological agendas.
</p>

<h3>
Presentation 2: EnCall Me Sheep: How looking at the social interactions
of sheep can change human perceptions
</h3>

<h3>
Author
</h3>
<p>Marika S. Bell</p>

<h4>Speaker: Marika S. Bell (Homeward Pet Adoption Centre)
</h4>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>Research into animal relationships can be used for interacting and
understanding other animals; how perceptions can be altered by research,
presented in a way that allows animal relationships to be recognized by
humans in terms of ‘friendship’, i.e., choosing to spend time with specified
others, (Seyfarth &amp; Cheney 2012; Christakis &amp; Fowler 2014). This
recognition of choice regarding friendships with other beings, demonstrate
their potential as ‘persons’ (Latour 2005; Bekoff 2001). It follows that they
can form friendships similar to human friendships and are demonstrated in
ways recognizable to human-people due to ‘embodied knowledge’
(Hamington 2008) of the feelings and actions associated with friendship.

This recognition can be held as evidence that other animals, in this case
sheep, have an innate right to personhood and moral consideration. Lastly,
this methodology can be utilized for those who work with other-than-human
animals to better know other animals as persons.
</p>
