<h3>Presentation 3: „One of them came to us”: how sanctuaries as spaces
of care enable human and nonhuman animals to advocate together
</h3>
<h3>
Author
</h3>
<p>
Maria Martelli
</p>
<h4>Speaker: Maria Martelli (Institute for Social Solidarity) </h4>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>Farmed animal sanctuaries (FAS) are places of refuge, care and advocacy
for nonhuman animals (Donaldson &amp; Kymlicka, 2015). Moreover, they are
spaces that make possible the rescue of nonhuman animals (NAs). This
research looks at how, often, rescue operations are conducted based on
interactions between NAs and humans. It has been said that “animals are
their best advocates” (Villanueva, 2019), and that listening to their voices
(Meijer, 2019) is best practice. In this vain, this research explores how NAs
advocate for themselves, expressing their wishes to live and be cared for.
Using qualitative methods - interviews with human guardians/workers of
two FAS in Romania - this research explores the interactions that led to the
relocation of particular NAs to sanctuary space. These relationships are
often based on physical proximity, and their success depends both on the
humans’ ability to listen, as well as on the NAs’ ability to communicate their
needs.
</p>

<h3>
Presentation 4: The cognitive assessment model: A framework for
how humans judge animals
</h3>
<h3>
Authors
</h3>
<p>Wen Zhou, Anne Littlewood, &amp; Brian Hare</p>

<h4>Speaker: Wen Zhou (Duke University)</h4>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Animals play important roles in human society ranging from food sources to
human companions. How do humans evaluate animals and assign them
different roles? Here we propose the cognitive assessment model that
people’s endorsement of the group-based hierarchy biases the perception
of animals’ mental life. These biased perceptions further shape beliefs
about animals’ roles. We examined 1487 participants from an online course
on co-evolution between dogs and humans. For each participant, we tested
their preference for the hierarchy of different dog breeds and presented six
pictures randomly selected from portraits of 45 dogs. Participants rated
each dogs’ cognitive capacities, pain sensitivity, social characters,
trustworthiness in different situations (e.g., with kids), and suitability for
different jobs (e.g., therapy). Results demonstrated correlations between
these variables and provided supporting evidence for the cognitive
assessment model. These findings will provide insight into the psychology
of human-animal relations and have implications for promoting animal
welfare.
</p>

